statement:
Consider the follow matrix \emph{A} and vector \textbf{b}:

\begin{align*}A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -1 \\ 1 & 0 \\ 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 2
\end{array}\right] \quad \mathbf{b} = \left[\begin{array}{c}
0 \\ 1 \\ 2 \\ 2
\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

Find the least squares solution \textbf{x} for the linear system
\emph{A\textbf{x} = \textbf{b}}. Use this to find a linear function
whose graph best fits the points \emph{(-1,0)}, \emph{(0,1)},
\emph{(1,2)}, and \emph{(2,2)} in $\mathbb{R}^2$.

sols:
The least squares solution vector $\hat{\mathbf x}$ is a 2x1 vector. We
can quickly find it using the normal equations.

\begin{align*}
A^T A \hat{\mathbf x} &= A^T \mathbf b \\
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 1 & 1 \\
-1 & 0 & 1 & 2
\end{array}\right] \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -1 \\ 1 & 0 \\ 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 2
\end{array}\right] \hat{\mathbf x} &= \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 1 & 1 \\
-1 & 0 & 1 & 2
\end{array}\right] \mathbf b \\
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
4 & 2 \\ 2 & 6
\end{array}\right] \hat{\mathbf x} &= \left[\begin{array}{c}
5 \\ 6
\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

To find $\hat{\mathbf x}$ from here we can either invert the matrix on
the left hand side, or use gaussian elimination. We choose the latter.

\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{cc|c}
4 & 2 & 5 \\ 2 & 6 & 6
\end{array}\right] \rightarrow 
\left[\begin{array}{cc|c}
1 & 3 & 3 \\ 4 & 2 & 5
\end{array}\right] \rightarrow 
\left[\begin{array}{cc|c}
1 & 3 & 3 \\ 0 & -10 & -7
\end{array}\right] \rightarrow 
\left[\begin{array}{cc|c}
1 & 0 & 9/10 \\ 0 & 1 & 7/10
\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

Hence

\begin{align*}\hat{\mathbf x} = \left[\begin{array}{c} 9/10 \\ 7/10 \end{array}\right]\end{align*}

Finally, how does this translate to the linear function whose graph best
fits the four given points? In other words, find \emph{m} and \emph{t}
such that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle
y = mx + t\end{align*} best fits the four given points
(\emph{x}\textsubscript{1},\emph{y}\textsubscript{1}),
(\emph{x}\textsubscript{2},\emph{y}\textsubscript{2}),
(\emph{x}\textsubscript{3},\emph{y}\textsubscript{3}),
(\emph{x}\textsubscript{4},\emph{y}\textsubscript{4}). To answer this we
need to understand how the matrix \emph{A} and the vector
\textbf{\emph{b}} were chosen. We notice that \textbf{\emph{b}} holds
the \emph{y} values. Further, the \emph{x} values of the points, are in
the second column of \emph{A}. The first column of \emph{A} is ones and
this is because the same constant \textbf{\emph{t}} appears for each
(x,y) pair. In matrix notation

\begin{align*}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & x_1 \\ 1 & x_2 \\ 1 & x_3 \\ 1 & x_4
\end{array}\right]
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\hat{\mathbf x}_1 \\ \hat{\mathbf x}_2
\end{array}\right] =
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
y_1 \\ y_2 \\ y_3 \\ y_4
\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

Reading $\mathbf b = A \hat{\mathbf x}$ line by line reveals

\begin{align*}y_j = 1 \hat{\mathbf x}_1 + x_j \hat{\mathbf x}_2 = \hat{\mathbf x}_2 x_j + \hat{\mathbf x}_1 = 7/10 x_j + 9/10\end{align*}
for \emph{j = 1,2,3,4}. Comparing to \emph{y = mx + t} we obtain

\begin{align*}m = 7/10, \quad t = 9/10\end{align*}

Therefore, the linear function is given by

\begin{align*}y = \frac7{10} x + \frac9{10}\end{align*}

